(52, NULL, NULL, 'Taste Experience Golden and Brown cane sugars', 1, 'page', 1, 4, NULL, 'twelve', NULL, 'tasteFaq', 'html', '<h4>Why do we have both large and small golden and brown sugar packs?</h4>\r\n<p>We have both listened to how our friends used these sugars and had first-hand experience which suggested not every recipe required a full 1kg of sugar. Waste is never good and so we have looked to reduce the frustration of storing lots of unused bags of sugar by offering both large and small packs.</p>\r\n<h4>Why are there two sizes/weights of both large packs and small packs?</h4>\r\n<p>Quite simply &ndash;&nbsp;&nbsp; sugars can have different moisture content and crystal sizes which give different volume. This results in some sugars having a variable bulk density which means that they can take up more or less room in the bag and require bigger and smaller bag.</p>\r\n<h4>What can I use the British inspired Golden Syrup cane sugar for?&nbsp;</h4>\r\n<p>This should be seen as the most exciting new sugar to have been launched in the UK in a generation. It has very distinctive taste profiles that truly present and hero the great flavour that this range of sugars offers. The Golden Syrup sugar is rich, bold and beautifully distinctive with a luscious, lingering sweetness. So it would enhance any cakes, glazes and desserts. Look for more great &ldquo;inspired&rdquo; recipes on the Golden Syrup Sugar webpage.</p>\r\n<h4>Where do the inspirations from these sugars come from?</h4>\r\n<p>The inspirations are drawn from the true histories and geographies that have helped inspire bringing together this collection and great variation of different sugar types. They reflect processes, styles and key cane sugar production areas across the globe that Tate &amp; Lyle Sugars has had a relationship with.</p>\r\n<h4>Are these not your old brown sugars simply in new packaging?</h4>\r\n<p>No, except for Demerara, these are all entirely new sugars that have been produced to optimise their distinct flavour profiles in order to create an effective range of different brown and golden sugars with clear and understandable distinctly different uses.</p>\r\n<h4>Do you coat white sugar with molasses?</h4>\r\n<p>No we are not coating white refined sugar with molasses. Like all other cane sugar products we vary the degree of molasses coating on the sugar crystal.</p>\r\n<h4>Are your sugars mingled?</h4>\r\n<p>Mingling is a name used for a valuable industrial process within the sugar industry which enables our skilled production team to blend the best flavours using differing degrees of molasses. So like a mixologist or a coffee baristas, yes we blend the best flavours to deliver the best results and great tasting flavour. All different brown and golden sugars have by definition varying degrees of molasses content to enable them to be uniquely different.</p>', NULL),
(53, NULL, NULL, 'Light at HeartÂ®', 1, 'page', 1, 5, NULL, 'twelve', NULL, 'heartFaq', 'html', '<h4>What is Light at Heart&reg;?</h4>\r\n<p>Light at Heart&reg; contains 100% naturally sourced ingredients including pure cane sugar, sweet Stevia plant leaf extract and natural flavour. It is available in both 450g white and brown varieties, so it can help you cook with versatility and enjoy fantastic results.</p>\r\n<h4>Where is Light at Heart&rsquo;s Stevia sourced from?</h4>\r\n<p>Currently we source our Stevia leaf extract from China.</p>\r\n<h4>Why combine sugar with Stevia?</h4>\r\n<p>We believe that you should not have to compromise taste and performance when seeking lower calorie solutions. By blending together cane sugar and stevia, we are able to offer a product which is twice as sweet as sugar saving 50% less calories in usage (as you only need to use half as much). The result: a lower calorie sugar solution that does not compromise on taste, texture or versatility. And we&rsquo;ve managed to do it using just naturally sourced ingredients!</p>\r\n<h4>Why does Light at Heart&reg; contain a natural flavouring?</h4>\r\n<p>A natural flavour is added to prevent the liquorice aftertaste of Stevia coming through; hence it helps the sweet leaf extract to taste sweet like sugar. It&rsquo;s a flavour from a natural source. At a technical level the natural sugar and Stevia blend is stable at cooking temperatures. Have a go and why not try our great recipes. Hope you will be as much impressed by the results as we were when trying them.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h4>Is Light at Heart&reg; made from 100% natural sourced ingredients?</h4>\r\n<p>Yes, all the ingredients in both white and brown Light at Heart&reg; variants are 100% naturally sourced.</p>\r\n<h4>Why is Light at Heart&reg; available in a white and brown variant?</h4>\r\n<p>As with normal sugar there is a market for both brown and white sugar. Many consumers use white as a staple sugar and brown for adding specifically to coffee or for baking. Our brown sugar blend is made from Demerara sugar which has a rich, creamy, molasses-like flavour which enhances the taste of many baked goods.</p>\r\n<h4>Can I use Light at Heart&reg; just like I use regular sugar?</h4>\r\n<p>Yes and our recipes should prove you how great it is to cook with Light at Heart&reg;! Using Light at Heart&reg; could not be simpler.&nbsp; Simply replace sugar with half the quantity of Light at Heart and progress as you would normally. This applies for anything from sweetening your tea to baking cakes.</p>\r\n<h4>Is Light at Heart&reg; good for baking?</h4>\r\n<p>Yes and we hope that our recipes should prove you that using Light at Heart&reg; lets you achieve the same texture, taste &amp; sweetness you would expect from something cooked containing regular sugar. The good news is it will have fewer calories because you only need to use half as much Light at Heart&reg; as you would sugar.</p>', NULL),
(54, NULL, NULL, 'Usage', 1, 'page', 1, 6, NULL, 'twelve', NULL, 'usageFaq', 'html', '<h4>Can I use Light at Heart&reg; just like I use regular sugar?</h4>\r\n<p>Yes and our recipes should prove you how great it is to cook with Light at Heart&reg;! Using Light at Heart&reg; could not be simpler.&nbsp; Simply replace sugar with half the quantity of Light at Heart and progress as you would normally. This applies for anything from sweetening your tea to baking cakes.</p>\r\n<h4>Is Light at Heart&reg; good for baking?</h4>\r\n<p>Yes and we hope that our recipes should prove you that using Light at Heart&reg; lets you achieve the same texture, taste &amp; sweetness you would expect from something cooked containing regular sugar. The good news is it will have fewer calories because you only need to use half as much Light at Heart&reg; as you would sugar.</p>', NULL),
