(298, NULL, NULL, 'Gooey Chocolate Pud Instructions', 1, 'page', 0, 2, NULL, 'twelve', NULL, NULL, 'html', '<ol>\r\n<li class="step-1">Preheat the oven to 180&ordm;C/Gas 4 (if using a fan-assisted oven adjust the temperature according to instructions). Sift the flour, cocoa powder and baking powder into a bowl and rub in the butter. Stir in&nbsp;Tate &amp; Lyle Light at Heart Brown, almonds and mix in the milk until smooth. Spoon into a deep, 2 litre round oven-proof dish and level the surface.</li>\r\n<li class="step-2">For the sauce mix together the&nbsp;Tate &amp; Lyle Light at Heart Brown&nbsp;and cocoa powder and whisk in the boiling water. Pour the cocoa liquid over the pudding and bake for 30-40 minutes (placed on a baking sheet) or until the top is firm and there is a lovely dark sauce at the bottom.</li>\r\n<li class="step-3">Leave to stand for just a minute or two before serving (the sauce will be absorbed by the sponge if left to stand too long). Dust with&nbsp;Tate &amp; Lyle Fairtrade Icing Cane Sugar. Spoon into dishes and serve with frozen raspberries.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<h4 class="ir">GET THE KIDS INVOLVED:</h4>\r\n<p>Kids will enjoy making chocolate icing sugar to sieve on top - 1 part cocoa powder, 2 parts icing sugar.</p>\r\n<h4 class="ir">TIP:</h4>\r\n<p>The deeper the dish the longer the cooking time, so depending on the depth of your dish, take a peek 5-10 minutes before the end of the recommended time.</p>', NULL),
(299, NULL, NULL, 'Gooey Chocolate Pud ingredients', 1, 'page', 0, 3, NULL, 'twelve', NULL, NULL, 'html', '<h4>For the pudding</h4>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li class="lah">85g Tate &amp; Lyle Light at Heart Brown</li>\r\n<li>175g self raising flour</li>\r\n<li>50g cocoa powder</li>\r\n<li>1 tsp baking powder</li>\r\n<li>85g butter</li>\r\n<li>50g ground almonds</li>\r\n<li>250ml skimmed milk</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h4>And for the sauce&hellip;</h4>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>50g Tate &amp; Lyle Light at Heart Brown</li>\r\n<li>25g cocoa powder</li>\r\n<li>600ml boiling water</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h4>Finally, to serve&hellip;</h4>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Tate &amp; Lyle Fairtrade Icing Cane Sugar for dusting</li>\r\n<li>Approximately 250g frozen raspberries</li>\r\n</ul>', NULL),
(300, NULL, NULL, 'Gooey Chocolate Pud nutritional information', 1, 'page', 0, 4, NULL, 'twelve', NULL, NULL, 'html', '<table >\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td >\r\n\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p><strong>Values per serving</strong></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p><strong>Women`s GDA per serving</strong></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p><strong>Typical GDA Values (Women)</strong></p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td >\r\n<p><strong>Energy (kcal)</strong></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>1288</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>15%&nbsp;</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n\r\n<p>2000 kcal</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td >\r\n<p><strong>Energy (kJ)</strong></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>307</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>N/A</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td >\r\n<p><strong>Protein (g)</strong></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>6.6</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>15%</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n\r\n<p>45g</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td >\r\n<p><strong>Carbohydrates (g)</strong></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>37.9</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>17%</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n\r\n<p>230g</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td >\r\n<p><strong>of which sugars (g)</strong></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>20.2</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>22%</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n\r\n<p>90g</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td >\r\n<p><strong>Fat (g)</strong></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>14.7</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>21%</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n\r\n<p>70g</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td >\r\n<p><strong>Of which saturated fat (g)</strong></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>7.1</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>36%</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n\r\n<p>20g</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td >\r\n<p><strong>Fibre (g)</strong></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>3.1</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>13%</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>24g</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td >\r\n<p><strong>Salt (g)</strong></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>0.8</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>13%</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>6g</p>\r\n\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>', NULL),
(301, NULL, NULL, 'METHOD', 1, 'page', 0, 1, NULL, 'twelve', NULL, NULL, 'html', '<ol>\r\n<li>Pre-heat the oven to 180&ordm;C/Gas 4 (if using a fan-assisted oven adjust the temperature according to instructions). Grease and line an 18cm square tin.</li>\r\n<li>Pop the chopped chocolate and butter into a heat proof bowl and set over a pan of very gently simmering water to melt, making sure the bottom of your bowl isn''t touching the water. Stir frequently. (It&rsquo;s not a good idea to do this in the microwave as the chocolate can easily overheat). Carefully remove the bowl from the heat and leave to cool.</li>\r\n<li>Lightly beat the eggs and egg yolk with 2 tbsp of cold water. Stir the Tate &amp; Lyle Light at Heart White&nbsp;into the chocolate, followed by the egg mixture. Sift in the flour and baking powder and gently fold together using a large metal spoon. Pour into the tin and bake for 20-30 minutes (check after 20 minutes; if you overcook them the brownies may be a little too dry). Leave to cool in the tin and then turn out on to a chopping board. Cut into 16 squares.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<h4>TIP:</h4>\r\n<p>If you want a less rich brownie, use dark Belgian cooking chocolate with 50% cocoa solids instead. A good tip for not overcooking brownies is that you want a cake skewer to come out with a little bit of mixture left on it, with the edges cooked and browned, but the middle less firm. The longer you leave the brownies without cutting them, the better (24 hours is ideal).</p>', NULL),
(302, NULL, NULL, 'INGREDIENTS', 1, 'page', 0, 2, NULL, 'twelve', NULL, NULL, 'html', '<ul>\r\n<li>125g Tate &amp; Lyle Light at Heart White</li>\r\n<li>200g dark cooks&rsquo; chocolate, 72% cocoa solids, chopped into chunks</li>\r\n<li>150g butter, cubed</li>\r\n<li>3 medium free range eggs and 1 egg yolk</li>\r\n<li>2 tbsp cold water</li>\r\n<li>85g self raising flour</li>\r\n<li>1 tsp baking powder</li>\r\n</ul>', NULL),
(303, NULL, NULL, 'Hazelnut And Cranberry Biscuits Instructions', 1, 'page', 0, 1, NULL, 'twelve', NULL, NULL, 'html', '<ol>\r\n<li class="step-1">Preheat the oven to 180&ordm;C/Gas 4 (if using a fan-assisted oven adjust temperature according to instructions). Line a baking sheet with greaseproof paper.</li>\r\n<li class="step-2">Sift the flour and baking powder into a bowl then stir in all the remaining ingredients. Start to pull the stiff mixture together using your hands. Knead the mixture well on a lightly floured work surface for at least 2-3 minutes.</li>\r\n<li class="step-3">Roll the dough into a long sausage shape and gently flatten. Place on a baking sheet and bake for 20-25 minutes or until it is golden and feels firm when pressed. Leave to cool for 10 minutes then cut the log into 12 slices on the diagonal (at an angle of about 45 degrees) and bake again for 5-10 minutes or until golden, turning over once. Remove from the baking sheet and leave to cool on a wire rack.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<h4 class="ir">GET THE KIDS INVOLVED:</h4>\r\n<p class="ir">Kids love kneading the dough and rolling it into a long sausage shape.</p>\r\n<h4 class="ir">TIP:</h4>\r\n<p class="ir">Serve these deliciously crisp biscuits to dunk in hot chocolate, espresso coffee or vin santo.</p>', NULL),
(304, NULL, NULL, 'Hazelnut And Cranberry Biscuits Ingredients', 1, 'page', 0, 2, NULL, 'twelve', NULL, NULL, 'html', '<ul>\r\n<li class="lah">40g Tate &amp; Lyle Light at Heart Brown</li>\r\n<li>175g plain flour</li>\r\n<li>&frac14; tsp baking powder</li>\r\n<li>2 medium free range eggs, beaten</li>\r\n<li>&frac12; tsp almond extract, optional</li>\r\n<li>60g dried cranberries</li>\r\n<li>60g blanched hazelnuts or blanched almonds, roughly chopped</li>\r\n</ul>', NULL),
