(362, NULL, NULL, 'Our Picks for April', 1, 'page', 1, 1, NULL, 'twelve', NULL, NULL, 'html', '<p>The days will soon be getting longer and it might not feel like it but spring is set to be in full swing very soon, which means that we can look forward to the gloriously fresh ingredients that April has in store for us.</p>', NULL),
(363, NULL, NULL, 'Quintessentially British Lamb', 1, 'page', 1, 2, 'leftContentBlock', 'six', NULL, NULL, 'html', '<p>April is a time for patriotic celebration &ndash; St George&rsquo;s Day is 23rd April, so we reckon that a quintessentially British lamb dish is a real highlight at this time of year. Our recipe for <a href="/recipe/slow-cooked-melting-lamb-shanks">Slow Cooked Melting Lamb Shanks</a> uses a fantastic combination of red onions, red wine vinegar and raisins to create a deep, intense flavour that warms the heart and tickles the taste buds!&nbsp;</p>', NULL),
(364, NULL, NULL, 'Lamb shanks', 1, 'page', 0, 3, NULL, 'six', 'original', NULL, 'image', NULL, NULL),
(365, NULL, NULL, 'Strawberry Tarts', 1, 'page', 1, 4, 'leftContentBlock', 'six', NULL, NULL, 'html', '<p>And to top it off? As stunning to look at as they are to eat, strawberries will just be coming into season this month. Having long been a key feature in classic British summer desserts, they are perfect for injecting a little sunshine into your kitchen &ndash; even on the dreariest of days! We love these luscious <a href="/recipe/strawberry-tarts">Strawberry Tarts</a>, which look and taste divine and are perfect for both dinner parties and picnics. &nbsp;The best part is that they are beautifully easy to prepare, so it&rsquo;s a fantastic recipe to get the little ones involved with too!</p>', NULL),
(366, NULL, NULL, 'strawb tarts', 1, 'page', 0, 5, NULL, 'six', 'original', NULL, 'image', NULL, NULL),
(367, NULL, NULL, 'Getting started', 1, 'page', 1, 1, 'clearBoth leftContentBlock', 'six', NULL, NULL, 'html', '<p>We knew it was important that each of the rooms in the house looked visually very different, inspiring and were excitingly disruptive. Above all else we were defied to create all the edible treats and a masterpiece in one room only using one type of sugar from the new range of Taste Experience sugars and to have enough to be eaten across three days. But this ended up becoming a delight and the beauty of the brief. So for example we chose to have a lot of sponge cakes in the British inspired Golden Syrup sugar room as the lovely Lorna Wing had recommended that it tastes delicious in feather light sponges. We came up with lots of &ldquo;sweet&rdquo; ideas such as having hundreds of macaroons all around the stairs, edible cousins or flowers, a carpet made of meringues&hellip;</p>', NULL),
(368, NULL, NULL, 'The challenge', 1, 'page', 1, 1, NULL, 'twelve', NULL, NULL, 'html', '<p>We asked the one and only ''curator of cake'' in the world, Miss Cakehead, to help us create the ultimate Tasting House. Here''s what she has to say about it...</p>', NULL),
(369, NULL, 440, 'british', 1, 'page', 0, 2, NULL, 'six', 'original', NULL, 'youtube', NULL, NULL),
(370, NULL, NULL, 'Hush hush', 1, 'page', 1, 3, 'clearBoth leftContentBlock', 'six', NULL, NULL, 'html', '<p>When developing ideas, the &ldquo;Eat Year Heart Out Team&rdquo; of cake makers worked as a group in a secret forum so it was very much a team effort, dotted with my list of &ldquo;Must Haves&rdquo; &ndash; including a sea turtle cake, Mayan temple, a rainbow cake which was at least 5ft long and a giant Easter Island Head Cake. &nbsp;</p>', NULL),
(371, NULL, NULL, 'Turtle', 1, 'page', 0, 4, NULL, 'six', 'original', NULL, 'image', NULL, NULL),
(372, NULL, NULL, 'The team', 1, 'page', 1, 5, 'clearBoth leftContentBlock', 'six', NULL, NULL, 'html', '<p>When it came to allocating the work I purpose fully chose cake makers whose style would work with each of the rooms. We also had to recruit new food artists specifically for the project to do the ridiculously pretty cakes &amp; cookies on offer.&nbsp; The full role call of the incredible cake artists who took part includes:</p>\r\n<p><strong>British Inspired &ndash; Golden Syrup cane sugar<br /></strong>Kate Shirazi, (Cakeadoodledo)<br />Rosalind Miller, All Mine Patisserie, Eat My Flowers, Sarah King, Carina&rsquo;s Cupcakes</p>\r\n<p><strong>Caribbean Inspired - &nbsp;Light Muscovado cane sugar</strong><br />Sarah Hardy (Sarah Hardy Cakes) and Juliet Sear (Fancy Nancy Cakes)</p>\r\n<p><strong>Mediterranean Inspired &ndash; Light Soft Brown cane sugar</strong><br />Carina&rsquo;s Cupcakes<br />The Meringue Girls<br />Jenni Powell (Two Little Cats Bakery)</p>\r\n<p><strong>Guyanese Inspired &ndash; Demarara cane sugar</strong><br />Daniel P Carter<br />Jenni Powell (Two Little Cats Bakery)<br />Kate Haigh (All Mine Patisserie)</p>\r\n<p><strong>Barbados Inspired &ndash; Dark Muscovado cane sugar</strong><br />Sarah Hardy Cakes<br />Nevie Pie Cakes</p>\r\n<p><strong>Mississippi Room &ndash; Dark Soft Brown cane sugar</strong><br />Jenni Powell (Two Little Cats Bakery)<br />Miss Insomnia Tulip<br />Annabel De Vetten (Conjurers Kitchen)</p>\r\n<p><strong>South Pacific Inspired &ndash; Golden Granulated cane sugar</strong><br />Annabel De Vetten (Conjurers Kitchen)<br />Sarah King</p>\r\n<p><strong>Mayan Room &ndash; Golden Caster cane sugar</strong><br />Chris Verrers (Cake for Breakfast)<br />Nevie Pie Cakes<br />All Mine Patisserie</p>\r\n<p><strong>General food styling</strong>&nbsp;<br />Nevie Pie Cakes with macaron bannisters by Miss Insomnia Tulip <br />Door Wreath Nevie Pie Cakes</p>', NULL),
(373, NULL, NULL, 'Let them eat cake and more...', 1, 'page', 1, 3, 'clearBoth leftContentBlock', 'six', NULL, NULL, 'html', '<p>Family, friends and neighbours were all grateful recipients of perfect and not-so-perfect samples. They willingly succumbed to glorious satiny meringues, feather-light sponges and indulgent pastel macaroons made with fine Mayan inspired <a href="/product/golden-caster-sugar">Golden Caster cane sugar</a>. South Pacific inspired <a href="/product/golden-granulated-sugar">Golden Granulated</a>, meanwhile, lent its gentle crunch to spiced nuts and brittle sugar-glazed tarts, while glistening Guyanese inspired <a href="/product/demerara-sugar">Demerara</a> added its amber crystals to buttery shortbreads and autumnal crumbles. Rich British inspired <a href="/product/golden-syrup-sugar">Golden-Syrup sugar</a>, the new kid on the block, and my favourite, made lusciously moist carrot cakes and traditional puddings.</p>\r\n<p>Next were the darker sugars, used for all sorts of sweet confections: Mediterranean inspired <a href="/product/light-soft-brown-sugar">Light Soft Brown</a> for caramelly popcorn, perfect for those curl-up-in-front-of-the-TV moments, and Caribbean inspired <a href="/product/light-muscovado-sugar">Light Muscovado</a> for rich and gooey brownies. Hearty stews were gently simmered and enhanced with a spoonful or two of malty Mississippi inspired <a href="/product/dark-soft-brown-sugar">Dark Soft Brown cane sugar</a>. Chutneys, Christmas cake and chocolate salami used up copious quantities of the treacly and deeply aromatic Barbados inspired <a href="/product/dark-muscovado-sugar">Dark Muscovado</a>.</p>', NULL),
(374, NULL, NULL, 'Sugar and spice and all things nice', 1, 'page', 1, 5, NULL, 'twelve', NULL, NULL, 'html', '<p>The testing done and dusted, the next part was to write up all the sugar sensory notes for the copy on the packs. Much like wine-tasting &ndash; though, sadly, there was no slurping or swirling &ndash; it was a matter of assessing the appearance, aroma, texture, mouth feel and finish of each to establish their complexity. The dictionary, the thesaurus, and a range of foodie features were consulted to inspire me to put pen to paper to accurately summarise these gorgeous sugars.</p>', NULL),
(375, NULL, NULL, 'Lights, camera, action', 1, 'page', 1, 6, 'clearBoth leftContentBlock', 'six', NULL, NULL, 'html', '<p>We hit the studio next to snap all the recipes, with the aim of really trying to make them look as natural as possible, with only the littlest of tweakings here and there &ndash; a few crumbs encouraged out of a biscuit or oozing cream teased from a sponge. There was no artful deceit, no sleight of hand, no faking it &ndash; just photographer Simon&rsquo;s patience, skilled lighting and food stylist Trish&rsquo;s immaculate attention to detail to show the food off to its best. While we were photographing the food we were being filmed ourselves to show a fly-on-the-wall video of what goes on behind the scenes on a shoot.</p>\r\n<p>On the home run, the penultimate part of my job was to help make four two-minute recipe videos for the website. They took three hours apiece, so the pace was full-on. A small army of people crowded into my kitchen. Food stylist Liz had sourced perfect pillar-box red strawberries, glossy cherries and out-of-season redcurrants, and, thankfully, knew the drill for keeping us all on schedule. Lucy, a props stylist with a great eye for current trends had provided all manner of kitchenalia for Kathryn, our hand model for the day, who deftly demonstrated all the dishes. Peter, the cameraman, took charge, while Declan and Mark, the creative team, Marion, Sugar Brand Manager, and I stood by, slightly superfluous, our job nearly done.&nbsp;</p>', NULL),
(376, NULL, NULL, 'âToutâ sweet', 1, 'page', 1, 8, 'clearBoth leftContentBlock', 'six', NULL, NULL, 'html', '<p>So, not quite a year on, all our hard work has come to fruition. The supermarket shelves are stacked high with the sugars and recipes are filtering into foodie magazines and websites. The imminent launch of the <a href="/blog/walk-into-our-tasting-house">Tasting House</a>, with its sugar-themed rooms is the culmination of the project. Fingers crossed that all of this will inspire, tempt and encourage expert and novice cooks alike into the kitchen to taste and experience the sugars for themselves.</p>', NULL),
(377, NULL, NULL, 'Favourites?', 1, 'page', 1, 8, NULL, 'twelve', NULL, NULL, 'html', '<p>Would you believe that to create this first edible Tasting House, it took a team of 14 cake makers, more than 2,000 hours to bake and 900 hours to decorate, and more than 600 kilos of Taste Experience range of cane sugars.</p>\r\n<p>And, the question everyone asks me if which room was my favorite?!.. I know you are not meant to pick one but I have to admit it was the Mayan room, my little slice of Eat Your Heart out in the tasting house, complete with a nod to the darker side of tribal culture.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><a href="http://cakeheadloves.moonfruit.com/" target="_blank">www.misscakehead.com<br /></a><a href="https://twitter.com/Miss_Cakehead" target="_blank">@miss_cakehead</a></p>', NULL),
